      <header>Re: &amp;RImportant&amp;n</header>
      <slot>10</slot>
      <level>210</level>
      <author>232688</author>
      <date>1052952256</date>
      <authorname>Amarinda</authorname>
      <text>This situation is in the limelight again. I'm not sure if everyone
realizes this or not, but if you tell someone no, they are going to
go to someone else right away. If it's something that you do feel
somewhat strongly about, send a mudmail to the other person that
works with you so they are aware ahead of time.

Lately, I've seen a great deal of tricks used. It's even been reported
that when a mort was told to see his GL, he asked if he could talk to
someone that was completely unrelated. Why would he do this? Because
the player felt -confident- that this person would say yes regardless
of the position he/she held. If you easily say yes to most offers or
issues that come your way, take a few moments to think on the people
that most often come to you and their history. Sometimes the problem
kids are easily identified.

And remember, if you don't know or you're uncomfortable with something,
there are a lot of avenues to take as far as questions or help goes.

&amp;r-&amp;wD&amp;n
</text>
